Maternal Smoking and Birth Weights

Prajwal Vijendra

September 26, 2018

Our questions of interest include the following.

Do mothers who smoke tend to give birth to babies with lower weights than mothers who do not smoke? What is a likely range for the difference in birth weights for smokers and non-smokers?

Is there any evidence that the association between smoking and birth weight differs by mother’s race? If so, characterize those differences.

Are there other interesting associations with birth weight with any other variable that are worth mentioning?

Let us check for interactions:

bwplot(babies_df$bwt.oz~ as.factor(babies_df$med) | as.factor(babies_df$mrace))

bwplot(babies_df$bwt.oz~as.factor(babies_df$mrace) | as.factor(babies_df$smoke))

xyplot(babies_df$bwt.oz~babies_df$parity | as.factor(babies_df$mrace))

xyplot(babies_df$bwt.oz~babies_df$parity | as.factor(babies_df$med))

xyplot(babies_df$bwt.oz~babies_df$mht | as.factor(babies_df$mrace))

xyplot(babies_df$bwt.oz~babies_df$inc | as.factor(babies_df$med))

Most of the inteteraction plots(xy and bw plots) does not show major signs of interaction. However, there seems to be interaction between the income and mother’s education. We can use this intercation in our linear model to see if helps improve our r^2.

Lets create linear models:

First let’s mean center noncategorical variable so that interpreation becomes easier.

babies_df$parity = babies_df$parity - mean(babies_df$parity)

babies_df$mage = babies_df$mage - mean(babies_df$mage)

babies_df$mht = babies_df$mht - mean(babies_df$mht)

babies_df$mpregwt = babies_df$mpregwt - mean(babies_df$mpregwt)

Let’s create a linear model by taking smoke, parity, age, mothers height, preg wt, mother race, mother education and income.

babies.lm = lm(bwt.oz~ as.factor(smoke) + parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + as.factor(med) + as.factor(inc),  data=babies_df)

We can see that we got r^2 of 0.1624, which is quite low and standard error is 16.75.

Taking different transformation such as log, quadratic and other transformation for diffrent variable did not seem to improve the r^2.

Also, tried creating linear model by taking diffrent interacation. The best r^2 I got is for the interaction between income and mother’s education (which we also saw earlier in the interaction plot).

babies.lm2 = lm(bwt.oz~ as.factor(smoke) + parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + as.factor(inc)*as.factor(med),  data=babies_df)

No point appear to have a huge leverage. So, we do not have to remove any points from our analysis.

To check if smoking tends to lowers babies weight, we can perform nested F test.

Nested F test:

model1: linear model by taking smoke, parity, age, mothers height, preg wt, mother race, mother education and income and interaction between income and education

model2:linear model by taking parity, age, mothers height, preg wt, mother race, mother education and income and interaction between income and education (not including smoking).

babies.lm2_nosmoking = lm(bwt.oz~ parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + as.factor(inc)*as.factor(med) + as.factor(inc)* as.factor(med),  data=babies_df)
anova(babies.lm2,babies.lm2_nosmoking)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: bwt.oz ~ as.factor(smoke) + parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + 
##     as.factor(inc) * as.factor(med)
## Model 2: bwt.oz ~ parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + as.factor(inc) * 
##     as.factor(med) + as.factor(inc) * as.factor(med)
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F    Pr(>F)    
## 1    806 220962                                  
## 2    807 238843 -1    -17881 65.223 2.432e-15 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

We can see that the F statics is 65.223 and p value is 2.432e^-15. Since the p value is very small, we can conclude that based on the data, smoking indeed affects the baby weight.

Let’s perform t test to calculate the likely range for the difference in birth weights for smokers and non-smokers

t.test(babies_df$bwt.oz~babies_df$smoke, data= babies_df)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  babies_df$bwt.oz by babies_df$smoke
## t = 7.5415, df = 833.24, p-value = 1.215e-13
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   6.665042 11.355139
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        122.5386        113.5285

Based on the t-test we can see that the 95% confidence interval for the difference in birth weights for smokers and non-smokers is between 6.665 and 11.3551. We can also notice that the confidence interval does not include 0.

Check if smoking and birth weight differs by mother’s race

Lets plot how the interaction between baby’s weight and smoking differs by mothers race.

bwplot(babies_df$bwt.oz~as.factor(babies_df$smoke) | as.factor(babies_df$mrace))

Based on this plot, we can see that there is no visible interaction and all the plot looks similar. We can perform nested F test to be sure.

We can do this by perform a nested F test

babies.lm3 = lm(bwt.oz~ as.factor(smoke) + parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + as.factor(inc)*as.factor(med) + as.factor(smoke)*as.factor(mrace),  data=babies_df)
anova(babies.lm2,babies.lm3)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: bwt.oz ~ as.factor(smoke) + parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + 
##     as.factor(inc) * as.factor(med)
## Model 2: bwt.oz ~ as.factor(smoke) + parity + mage + mht + mpregwt + as.factor(mrace) + 
##     as.factor(inc) * as.factor(med) + as.factor(smoke) * as.factor(mrace)
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1    806 220962                           
## 2    802 219781  4    1180.8 1.0772 0.3666

Based on the nested F test the F statistic is 1.0772 and p value is 0.3666. Since, p value is high we can conclude that the association between mother’s race and smoking is not significant on baby’s weight.
